        <encodingDesc xml:lang="en">
            <samplingDecl xml:lang="en">
                <p xml:lang="en">The edition is based on the digital transcripts (HTML files wrapped in ePub) available from 
                    <ref target="http://shamela.ws/index.php/book/29676" xml:lang="en">
                        <foreign xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-ijmes">al-maktabat al-shāmila</foreign></ref>.</p>
            </samplingDecl>
            <editorialDecl xml:lang="en">
                <p xml:lang="en">The original editorial practices followed by 
                    <ref target="http://shamela.ws/index.php/book/29676" xml:lang="en">
                        <foreign xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-ijmes">al-maktabat al-shāmila</foreign></ref>can only be deduced from the limited mark-up found in the digital text
                    provided online and as ePub. It appears from that that paragraphs and head lines
                    were recorded and preserved. They also recorded page breaks, but at least for
                    the earlier issues these do not correspond to the page breaks in the print
                    edition and should thus be marked with 
                    <att xml:lang="en">ed</att>
                    =&quot;shamela&quot;</p>
                <p xml:lang="en">It remains unclear to which extent publication dates for individual
                    issues are correct. After reviewing the image files and the official publication schedule, the dates provided by 
                    <foreign xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-ijmes">hijrī</foreign>
                    seem to be correct</p>
                <p xml:lang="en">Some phenomena have been marked in red spans by 
                    <ref target="http://shamela.ws/index.php/book/29676" xml:lang="en">
                        <foreign xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-ijmes">al-maktabat al-shāmila</foreign></ref>. Red spans that contained three points only were considered indicators of
                    ellipses and transformed into 
                    <gi xml:lang="en">gap</gi>
                    with 
                    <att xml:lang="en">resp</att>
                    =&quot;#org_MS&quot;. Upon further scrutiny, it turned out that most, if
                    not all, of these 
                    <gi xml:lang="en">gap</gi>
                    s indicated the division between two
                    halfs of the line of a 
                    <foreign xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-ijmes">qaṣīda</foreign>
                    . I
                    have converted all 
                    <gi xml:lang="en">p</gi>
                    s that contained two short lines of
                    text divided by 
                    <gi xml:lang="en">gap</gi>
                    into 
                    <gi xml:lang="en">l</gi>
                    of
                        
                    <att xml:lang="en">type</att>
                    =&quot;bayt&quot; with 
                    <gi xml:lang="en">seg</gi>
                    child
                    elements. All other red spans have been rendered as 
                    <gi xml:lang="en">gap</gi>
                    .</p>
            </editorialDecl>
        </encodingDesc>
        <profileDesc xml:lang="en">
            <!-- as we deal with sources from an area and period which also used non-Latin scripts and preferred a number of calenders over the Gregorian, this should be declared here -->
            <calendarDesc xml:lang="en">
                <calendar xml:id="cal_gregorian" xml:lang="en">
                    <p xml:lang="en">Following the hegemonial approach of standards rooted in the
                        English language, the Gregorian calendar is presumed as the norm and must
                        not be specified.</p>
                    <p xml:lang="en">The 
                        <att xml:lang="en">when</att>
                        attribute always provides W3C
                        dates, while the 
                        <att xml:lang="en">when-custom</att>
                        attribute follows the
                        inherent logic of the chosen calendar.</p>
                    <p xml:lang="en">E.g. 
                        <date when="1841-05-23" xml:lang="en">23 May 1841,
                            Sunday</date>
                        , 
                        <date when="1908-03-05" xml:lang="en">5 Mar 1908,
                            Thursday</date>
                        .</p>
                </calendar>
                <calendar xml:id="cal_islamic" xml:lang="en">
                    <p xml:lang="en">Islamic 
                        <hi xml:lang="en">hijrī</hi>
                        calendar: lunar calendar
                        beginning the Year with 1 Muḥarram. Dates differ between locations as the
                        beginning of the month is based on sightings of the new moon.</p>
                    <p xml:lang="en">E.g. 
                        <date calendar="#cal_islamic" datingMethod="#cal_islamic" when="1841-05-23" when-custom="1257-04-01" xml:lang="en">1 Rab II 1257,
                            Sunday</date>
                        , 
                        <date calendar="#cal_islamic" datingMethod="#cal_islamic" when="1908-03-05" when-custom="1326-02-01" xml:lang="en">1 Ṣaf 1326,
                            Thursday</date>
                        .</p>
                </calendar>
                <calendar xml:id="cal_julian" xml:lang="en">
                    <p xml:lang="en">Reformed Julian calendar beginning the Year with 1 January. In
                        the Ottoman context usually referred to as 
                        <hi xml:lang="en">rūmī</hi>
                        .
                        Arabic newspapers usually labelled this calendar as 
                        <hi xml:lang="en">sharqī</hi>
                        .</p>
                    <p xml:lang="en">All solar calendars add an intercalated 366th day every fourth
                        (and, in the case of Gregorian and rūmī calendars, even-numbered) year at
                        the end of February (the last day of the old Julian calendar). The Gregorian
                        calendar suppresses this rule in centesimal years that cannot be divided by
                        400. This difference creates a growing offset between Gregorian and Julian
                        calendars: while 1900 R was a leap year, 1900 was not, which in turn caused
                        the difference between the Gregorian calendar, on the one hand, and the 
                        <hi xml:lang="en">mālī</hi>
                        and 
                        <hi xml:lang="en">rūmī</hi>
                        calendars, on
                        the other, to grow from 12 to 13 days from 29 Shubāṭ (February) 1900 R /
                        1315 M (13 March 1900) onwards.</p>
                    <p xml:lang="en">E.g. 
                        <date calendar="#cal_julian" datingMethod="#cal_julian" when="1841-05-23" when-custom="1841-05-11" xml:lang="en">11 Ayyār 1841,
                            Sunday</date>
                        , 
                        <date calendar="#cal_julian" datingMethod="#cal_julian" when="1908-03-05" when-custom="1908-02-21" xml:lang="en">21 Shub 1908,
                            Thursday</date>
                        .</p>
                </calendar>
                <calendar xml:id="cal_ottomanfiscal" xml:lang="en">
                    <p xml:lang="en">Ottoman fiscal calendar: a lunosolar calendar. It is based on
                        the Old Julian calendar beginning the Year with 1 March. Introduced as
                        fiscal calendar in 1676 and in the Ottoman context usually referred to as
                            
                        <hi xml:lang="en">mālī</hi>
                        and sometimes, confusingly, also as 
                        <hi xml:lang="en">rūmī</hi>
                        . Every 33 lunar years, a 
                        <hi xml:lang="en">hijrī</hi>
                        year would complete within a single solar 
                        <hi xml:lang="en">mālī</hi>
                        year. In this case the counting of the 
                        <hi xml:lang="en">mālī</hi>
                        years skipped a year to catch up with the faster 
                        <hi xml:lang="en">hijrī</hi>
                        calendar. Due to a printing error in the coupon
                        booklets for the consolidated debt repayment program for 1872 (1288 M
                        instead of 1289 M), synchronisation of 
                        <hi xml:lang="en">mālī</hi>
                        and 
                        <hi xml:lang="en">hijrī</hi>
                        years was henceforth abolished. As 
                        <hi xml:lang="en">mālī</hi>
                        years began with 1 March, 
                        <hi xml:lang="en">mālī</hi>
                        leap years preceded their 
                        <hi xml:lang="en">rūmī</hi>
                        and
                        Gregorian counterpart (the leap year 1315 M commenced on 13 March 1899).</p>
                    <p xml:lang="en">E.g. 
                        <date calendar="#cal_ottomanfiscal" datingMethod="#cal_ottomanfiscal" when="1841-05-23" when-custom="1257-03-11" xml:lang="en">11 Māyis 1257, Sunday</date>
                        ,
                            
                        <date calendar="#cal_ottomanfiscal" datingMethod="#cal_ottomanfiscal" when="1908-03-05" when-custom="1323-12-21" xml:lang="en">21 Shub 1323,
                            Thursday</date>
                        .</p>
                </calendar>
